{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689937/1958051601/0174.xml":{"full_text":"TH! KRY WIST CITIZIN Friday, May 16, IMS\nPage 6\n\u00aehr Keg West (Hittm\nPublished Sunday Morning and Every Week Day Afternoon,\nExcept Saturday\nNoRMAX n AKTMAN Editor Publlaher\nMargaret &rmmanTZ3ZZZ t city Editor\nCULT RILEY Advertising Manager\nRAYFORD ROBERTS Circulation Managar\nPERCT CURRY Mechanical Superintendent\nMEMBER OF ASSOCIATED PRESS\nEatared at Kay Want, Florida as\nSecond Claoa Matter\nCARRIER SUBSCRIPTION RATES\nTeer H\u00bb\nMon the 'f u\n1 Month IM\n1 Wook\nMAIL RATES\n1 Tear IIFSO\nMunthe\nI Mentha 4 40\n1 Month 1.7 S\n(No weekly 'nail eubscrlptfone Accepted)\nNATIONAL ADVERTISING REPRESENTATIVES:\nTHEIS SIMPSON CO. INC.\n1 K 14th St., Now fork St, N. T.\nBranch Offlcoa In Principal Cltleo\nMore Trailer Parks Okay\nOutside City Limits\nWe at The Citizen, while we are not against well*\nrun trailer parks, generally, do not favor the expansion\nof the Stadium Mobile Home Park coming up for the\ncity commission\u2019s consideration soon.\nThe city planning commission, by a split vote of,\n8 to 3, decided last Monday night to recommend the\nexpansion be approved. Most of the plan commissioners\nvoting \u201cyes\u201d said they did so because more people at\nHie public hearing spoke in favor of the expansion than\nspoke against it.\nMany of the people who spoke up pointed out that\nStadium Park is a very rigidly-restricted, well-run op\neration and the land the park owner hopes to put more\ntrailers on is located near the football stadium and the\nPoinciana multiple-housing project.\nAll this is very true.\nThe land may not be ideal for homes.\nBut here in Key West, with the island as small as\nit is, most land is really not \u201cideal\u201d for homes, if one\ngoes by the usual rules. We live too closely together;\nhomes and businesses, homes and apartment houses,\nhomes and schools or public facilities simply cannot be\nseparated by the wide \u201cneutral zones\u201d possible in big\nger places.\nThis very lack of available land for building houses\nis the reason, and just about the only reason, that we\noppose the expansion of the Stadium Park. It\u2019s going to\neover some 850 by 875 feet of land some distance off\nFlagler and about 600 feet from Roosevelt Boulevard.\nThat area is directly in the path the city\u2019s growth is\ntaking now.\nIt\u2019s probably true, also, that if the land climbed\naky-high in value, the trailer park owners would sell.\nThey\u2019d need to be offered very good prices, however,\nto make up for their own expenses in putting water\nhookups, fill, street and curb and playground improve\nments into the park\u2014and the prices would tend to dis-1\ncourage prospective buyers, looking for a lot on which\nto build a low-priced house.\nWe aren\u2019t opposed to trailers as such.\nMany fine families use them here.\nIn a Navy town, or any town with a large number\nof married servicemen constantly passing through, there\nmust be room for those who own these mobile homes..\nBut we must also try to see that the small amount of\nland we have left on this island is developed in the full\nest possible way. It\u2019s strictly a matter of economics,\nbeauty and permanence, so far as we\u2019re concerned.\nWe thipk it\u2019s too bad that someone doesn\u2019t put in\na mobile home park of the type the Stadium Park own\ners are planning out on Stock Island. The distance from\ntown isn\u2019t very much greater\u2014after all, it\u2019s a long walk\nfrom the football stadium to the Naval Station or the\ncomer of Truman and Duval.\nOn Stock Island, there\u2019s plenty of room for such\ndevelopment and some of the trailer parks there could\nstand a good deal of beautification, landscaping and\ninore rigid rules and regulations. There, someone could,\ndevelop an actual \u201ctrailer city\u201d of the type seen in\nBradenton and other west coast Florida cities without t\nusing up land we need for houses and in a spot that\u2019s\nalmost equi-distant to the Naval Station and Boca Chica\nAir Station. To us, a mobile home center such as this\nwould seem ideal.\nCrossword Puzzle\nM. Watch\naecretly\n>5. Enzyme\n34 Gaseous\nelement\nM. Beverage\nN. Army\n\u2022Meer: abbr.\n44. Neither\nanimal nor\nvetotable\n42. English\nletter\n43. Froated\n45. Examina\ntion\n47. Lessened\n49 Region in\nSpain\nSI. Sort\n52. Report\n54. Hail\n55. Shelter\n54. Marsh bird\nACMM\nl.Of bh\u00ab\n4. Destinies\nI. Behave\nM. Small\nanimal\n11. Aeeustom\n14. Low\n11. Diedams\n17. Emphasise\n11. Frank\nTalk wildly\n>l. Millimeter:\nabbr.\n22 Flannod\n34 For e\u00bbm\npie: abbr.\nM. Flow baek\n30 Jeweler's\nwe.fht\n>l. Wine vessel\n32. Appointed\nto arrive\n33 Knock\np RioCTiis oMaio\nI&|ejt swelgi 1 sms[p|y|\n|dle\u2018n|s|emeMe|Ma|y|e|\nSolution of Yooterday\u2019a Puule\n17. Legal\naction\nDOWN\n1. Possessed\n2. Fireproof\n3. Cease\n4. Afr. fox\n5. Belgian\ncommune\n4. Symbol for\nthulium\n7. Age\nI. Close\nmouthed\nI. May it be\nso\n10. Meditative\n11. Small child\n14. Scarlet\n14. Bounder\n21. Decoration\nfor bravery\n23. Monitor\nlirard\n24. Turk,\ndecree\n35. Flavor\n27. More lively\nW. Honey\nmaker\n31. Judean king\n34. Horsemen\n37. Inherent\ncharacter\n40 Encountered\n41. Sea god\n44. Sweet\nbaked food\n44. Mark o*\nan injury\n47, Trouble\n44. Demand\npayment\n41. Swab\n50. Roman\nbronze\n53. Singing\nay liable\nIT WOULD HAVE TO GIVE SOMEPLACE\nJ cl\n\u25a0FF\u2019zji kA\nw V W a\nvMMMwTOhsz 'Frew\u00ae\nKF\u00ae- H F\nB IS\n\\|f\nW?\nm UN A\nS'Jy HI v\nIff\nJsB\u00ae\nA-\nSUNDAY SCHOOL LESSON\nGod's People Totted. Num. 13:\n17-14:45\nBy RALPH ROGERS\nIn the 7th chapter of Exodus we\nfind Moses beginning his conflict\nwith Pharaoh and the exodus be\ngins in the 12th chapter, then by\nthe time we reach the 19th chap\nter we find the Israelites at Mt.\nSinai.\nFollowing these events the rest\nof Exodus and Leviticus deals with\nthe laws and ceremonies which are\nto be observed. The story of the\nmovement from the \u201cMount of\nMoses\u201d to the arrival at their cen\ntral camp site begins in the 10th\nchapter of Numbers.\nThis camp was set up at Kadesh\nbarnea in the wilderness of Paran\nin the north-east part of the Sinai\npeninsula, about 70 miles south of\nHebron, which had a fine spring.\nThis water was insufficient how\never, but about five miles north\nwas a better watered area which\nwas promptly annexed to the cen\ntral camp. The time used in mak\ning this march covered a period of\n.about three years and it was from\nI this place the spies were sent into\nCanaan to spy out the land.\nMinority Report\nWhen the twelve spies returned\nto camp they were agreed on cer\ntain features. It was indeed a land\nof milk and honey. An Egyptian\npaper dated about 1900 B.C. writ\nten by Sinuhe describes it glowing\nly. \"Figs were in it, and grapes,\ni It had more wine than water. Plen\ntiful was its noney, abundant its\nolives. Every kind of fruit was on\nits trees. Barley was there, and\nemmer. There was no limit to any\nkind of cattle.\u201d\nThe spies agreed on the abun\ndant supply of good things. They\nalso agreed that it was strongly\ndefended and some called them\ngiants, the sons of Anak. These\ngiants were supposed to have des\ncended from a race of superhuman\nRALPH\nreally recession and how much i\nis just talk.\nMaybe that's not fair. Up\nNorth, there has been a level\ning-off period in buying lots of\nthings like washers, cars, TV\nsets and such\u2014\u2018but for heav\nen's sake, there has to be! Peo\nple have to wear out and use\nup and get tired of things be\nfore they buy new ones; and\nI think they're just about set to\ndo it, too.\nBut Not Hore\nAs far as Florida's concern\ned, though, we just don't have\na recession. We never did. We\nhad a lot of bad weather and\nthat was it\u2014the figures show\nit! As far as the state govern\nment being in such a fix, finan\ncially, they simply planned on\nthis past winter being much\nbigger than the winter before.\nIt wasn\u2019t bigger. It was about\nthe same. And that\u2019s where\nthey got stuck.\nThe farmers and fishermen\nhad a tough time. So did peo\nple selling motorboats, yachts,\ntickets to outdoor sports events\nand such. But night clubs and\ntaverns in most of Florida did\na booming business; heating\nfuel sales went up 78 per cent:\nand hotel, motel and apartment\nhouse business was only 4.35\nper cent lower than last win-.\nter\u2019s.\nAnd In Key West\nHere in Key West, we've\nbeen so much better off than\nmost of Florida that it isn't\neven funny\u2014our sales tax fig\nures, if you've followed them\nin the last few months, will\nprove it.\nThe bad weather hurt our\nor semidivine beings who wander\ned in the mists of primitive mytho\nlogy. \u201cAnak\u201d was the name of a\nrace rather than of an individual.\nThey may have been tall men but\nthey fell before the onslaught of\nJoshua (Joshua 11:21-22) and their\nchief city Hebron, became the pos\nsession of Caleb. They were giants\nto the imagination of the fear\nsmitten weaklings who brought\nback the majority report.\nBut Caleb quieted the congrega\ntion and he gave the minority re\nport. Here was a spy who was\nfearless and he knew that the God\nwho had led them to the border of\nthe Promised Land, would give\nthem the victory. He said, \u201cLet\nus go up at once, and possess it.\u201d\nIt's all nonsense that we are as\ngrasshopper! .as compared to the\nAnakim. His. suggestion was that\nthe Israelites march. God is on our\nside and we are greater than any\nrace of giants.\nWhere there is no vision, the\npeople perish and without ideals\nthe people are lost It takes faith\nin the leader to win the victory\nand when the leader is God, there\nshould be no fear. Only a spiritual\ncoward wants a religion without\nrisk or adventure. Let any con\ngregation propose expansion and\nthere will be some who shake their\nheads saying it can't be done\nbut if God is with that congrega\ntion it can and will be done.\nOne of my early congregations\nproposed expanding and improving\nthe 'old delapidated church build\ning. One of the leading members\ncontended the congregation was\npoor, they just didn't have the\nmoney, and besides this building\nwas good enough for our fathers,\nit ought to be good enough for us.\nThe faithful congregation over\nruled the high official churchman\nand the building was expanded\nand improved to the glory of God.\nWhere there's faith and a will, it\nWhere\u2019# This Recession\nWe Hear So Much About?\nBy RALPH ROBINSON, Manatar,\nKay West Trailer Sales\n\u201cBig recession\u2019\u2019 was the cry:\n\u201cOur state\u2019s in for doom and gloom.\u201d\nFigures show they\u2019re sort of wrong;\nBet we see another boom!\nI wonder how much of the so-called re\ncession that's been talked about so much is\nI shrimping industry; but it's\ncoming back. It hurt our char\nter boatmen and cut into our\nmotel receipts a little\u2014though\nnot so much\u2014but we re look\ning for a big bunch of summer\nj tourists, soon. A lot of people\nj who waited to take their vaca\ntions will be taking them now.\nThe Navy, Tee\nOur Navy base employment\nstayed pretty steady, too, and\nthat helped us a lot. The money\npaid to Navy men, their fami\ni lies and civilian workers prob\nably helped a great deal in\nkeeping us all \u201chealthy\u201d\nthrough a rough winter.\nMaybe a leveling-off period\nis a good thing, in away. It\nmakes factories, and merchants\nand everybody offer people\nmore for their money to get\ntheir business! But judging\nfrom the crowds who are still\nI stopping here at Key West\nTrailer Sales to see the new\n50-foot, two-bedroom Atlas \"10-\nI wide\u201d the Pacemaker people\ngot the idea before the reces\nsion talk ever started, when\nthey designed this whopper of\na home at such a price.\nPRizi WINNERS\nBy the way, the two U.S.\nNavy man who won the\nI \"grand prizes\" at our re\ncent open house festivities\nhave carried them heme.\nThe winners were Alfred\nManfra, 20-A Arthur Sawyer\nRd., who won the hi-fi ra\ndio phonograph combination\nand J. J. D'Ambrosio, 41-A\nArthur Sawyer Rd., who\ntppk homo the clock-radio.\ncan be done and the giants are\nonly imaginary.\nLoud Complaint*\nThe majority report of the weak\nkneed spies proved more popular.\nThe people did not want to risk\ntheir lives in taking the land.\nThey preferred to just go on allow\ning God to provide for them as he\nhad in the ten miracles shown in\ntheir brief journey in the wilder\nness. They began to weep and lift\ned up their voices all the night\nthrough. It would make interesting\nreading had some of the conversa\ntions among the people that night\nbeen recorded. They murmured\nagainst Moses for bringing them\ninto this forsaken place, and they\nwanted to go back to Egypt. They\nopenly revolted and contended\nthat it would have been better to\nhave died in Egypt. Fear became\na panic when the majority report\nwas given.\nMiss Ruth Paxon has brought\ninto sharp relief the contrast be\ntween the two groups, the ten and\nthe two: \u201cCaleb desired Canaan:\nthe ten despised Canaan. Caleb\nsought to enter the land; the ten\nslandered the land. Caleb had the\nspirit of an overcomer; the ten had\nthe spirit of one overcome. Caleb\nsaid. \u2018We are well able to over\ncome it'; the ten said, 'We are not\nable to go up against this people.\u2019\nCaleb looked up at God's promise\nand power; the ten saw giants.\nCaleb wholly followed the Lord his\nGod; the ten did not wholly follow\nthe Lord. Caleb and Joshua de\nclared that these giant races could\nno longer defend themselves, that\nis. \u2019the measure of the iniquity of\nthe Canaanites was not full, and\nthey were ripe for destruction.\u2019\n(Gen. 15:16; Lev. 18:25)\nThere will always be people who\nprefer death and slavery to pro\ngress and freedom. God will deal\nwith people of little faith as he did\nwith these rebellious children. The\nEmpire State building sways with\nthe wind. The joints are made\nloose so that the steel can bend\nwhereas the concrete would crack\nand crumple and break. Civiliza\ntion must be flexible that it might\nalso give and be flexible adjusting\nto the winds and turmoil of human\nstrife. Too many of us weep and\nEasy Banking\nBank from your car\nThat's the way some customers refer to banking\nfrom their cars at our Drive-In facility. Usually your\ntransaction is completed in a matter of seconds and\nyou're on your way. You, too, are invited to use this\nlatest banking convenience.\nENTRANCE TO DRIVE-IN WINDOW ON FRONT ST.\nFLORIDA\nNational Bank\nat KEY WEST\nCemer of Duval and Front Streets\nMEMBER FEDERAL DEPOSIT INSURANCE CORPORATION\nYour Friendly Community Bank\nToday\u2019s Business Mirror\nJ By SAM DAWSON\nNEW YORK (fl-lt\u2019i a spotty\nrecession we're having. And the\nchances are still good its rolling\nquality will continue and bring the\nnation through this upset in a fash\nion similar to others we\u2019ve experi\nenced since World War 11.\nThis spottiness shows up this\nweek in the official figures on\njust where the economy stands.\nWhile industrial production as a\nwhole is down more than 12 per\ncent from its peak, the total out\nput of goods and services is off\nonly four per cent.\nWhile consumer b u y 1 n g of\ndurable goods is down, purchases\nof soft goods and services are up.\nWhile factory payrolls are lower\nboth in number employed and in\ntotal pay, farm income is up.\nWhile production of capital\ngoods for industry and durable\ngoods for consumers continues to\nslide, home building is looking up\nand easier money is fostering the\nplans of states and local govern\nments to speed up construction of\nmany public works.\nThese are the things that the\ndull statistics tell have been hao\npening. They indicate that the roll\nng nature of the recession the\nbad times for some, especially the\nmakers of durable goods. bcin\u00ab\ncounter-balanced to some extent\nwail at the threat of the com\nmunist giants which to the weak\nlings they are as grasshoppers.\nSo long as we trust in God we\nshall conquer in His name.\nThere is always a penalty at\ntached to cowardice. \u201cIf you think\nyou are beaten, you are.\" \u201cSure\nly they shall not see the land which\nI sware unto their fathers, neither\nshall any of them that provoked\nme see it.\u201d God's faithful servant\nwas the exception together with\nJoshua.\nMoses prayer of intercession for\nhis rebellious people is one of faith\nand self-abnegation. There are\nmore prayers by Moses recorded in\nthe Old Testament than of any\nother servant of God. There is\nsome logic in his prayer also when\nhe says, if now Israel is destroyed\nthe knowledge of God will be lost.\n\u201cNow if thou shalt kill all this peo\nple as one man, then the nations\nwhich have heard the fame of thee\nwill speak saying. Because the\nLord was not able to bring this\npeople ink' the land which he\nsware unto them, therefore he hath\nslain them in the wilderness.\u201d\nGod is merciful, but those who\nfail to pass the test, take God at\nHis word through faith, must be\npunished. Because of their com\nplaint and grumbling it was de\ncreed that none twenty years of\nage or over should enter the prom\nised land. Joshua and Caleb were\nthe only exceptions. They passed\nthe test. For each of the forty\ndays spent in exploring the wilder\nness, they were to spend a year of\npunishment wandering in the wil\nderness. There is no escape from\nsin.\nRased on th* copyrighted out-\nHnee produced by th* Diviaion of\nChrietian Education, National\nCouncil of the Churchea of Chriat\nin th* U.S.A. and uaad by permla\naion.\nFURNITURE\nRefinishing Repair\nWILL REDECORATE\nYOUR FURNITURE\nTO LOOK LIKE NEW\nW* Also Specialize in\nFORMICA WORK\nSee or Call\nJOHN'S\nCABINET SHOP\n1012 Truman Ave. CY 4-1653\nby the good times for others in\n,tiU with us. The optimists count\non this to ward off a really bad\nslump and in time to cure present\nconditions.\nHare are the figures:\nThe nation's output of goods\nand services in the first three\nmonths of 1958 was at an annual\nrate of 422 billion dollars, com\npared with the record 440 billion\nset in the third quarter of 1937.\nBut the biggest drops came\nfrom two things: inventories were\nbeing, liquidated at a record post\nwar rate of nine billion dollars a\nyear, and purchases of equipment\nby business was off by 24 billion.\nNeither of these declines has run\nits course yet, but there s no rea\nson to suppose they can go on for\never, or even for much longer.\nConsumer purchases perhaps\nare being watched more closely\nthan any of the recession s other\nindicators. Buying of durable\ngoods is off nearly three billion\ndollars, but the rise in purchase\nof soft goods and services\ntrimmed the total loss to about IVi\nbillion. This leaves consumer\n(spending at an annual rate of\n281 Ie billion dollars.\nSpending for services has been\nrising steadily for months. The\nlatest annual rate is 108'4 billion\ndollars, which is one billion more\nthan in the final months of 1957.\nThe Federal Reserve Board\nchairman, William McChesney\nMartin Jr., also has some pleas\nant things to report.\nHe believes prices are now com\ning down in many areas, no mat\nter what the government s con\nsumer price index may seem to\nindicate to the contrary. Martin\nsays there's no question that ad\njustments in prices are being\nmade at the present time.\nAnd he finds that construction\nis looking up. The home building\nindustry looks healthier and states\nand communities are set to give\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN\nRadio and Television Listings\nCHANNEL 4 TV WTVJ\nFRIDAY EVENING\n\u2022U Sports 0:00 PhU Silvers\n<:B Weather 9.30 PlayhouM\nS:JO Renick lo w Une Up\nNewe iO:N Pera, to Pere, j\n\"aat 11:W Newa I\n7:N Harbor Com. 11:10 Weather\nTreekdowo tins Snort.\n1:30 Zane Grey 11:23 Movie\nSATURDAY MORNINO\nF\"**\u201d 10:30 Miohty Mouse\n2 iy'ss\u201d ,i: j\na:3O Cp. K'asare** 12:0